252
00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:21.700
Will you set your name down inthe scroll of youth

253
00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:24.570
that are written down old withall the characters of age?

254
00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:26.230
Have you not a moist eye,

255
00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:27.300
a dry hand,

256
00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:28.300
a yellow cheek,

257
00:12:28.300 --> 00:12:29.830
a white beard,

258
00:12:29.830 --> 00:12:31.000
a decreasing leg,

259
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:32.600
an increasing belly?

260
00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.500
Is not your voice broken,

261
00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:35.500
your wind short,

262
00:12:35.500 --> 00:12:36.370
your chin double,

263
00:12:36.370 --> 00:12:37.500
your wit single,

264
00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:40.700
and every part about you blastedwith antiquity?

265
00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:42.630
And yet will you call yourselfyoung?

266
00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:45.100
Fie, fie, fie, Sir John.

267
00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:50.130
My lord, I was born at about3:00 in the afternoon

268
00:12:50.130 --> 00:12:52.000
with a white head and somethingof a round belly.

269
00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.330
For my voice,

270
00:12:53.330 --> 00:12:57.430
I have lost it with halloing andsinging of anthems.

271
00:12:57.430 --> 00:13:02.470
The truth is, I'm only old injudgment and understanding.

272
00:13:02.470 --> 00:13:05.500
And he that will caper with mefor 1,000 marks,

273
00:13:05.500 --> 00:13:07.570
would him lend me the money andhave at him.

274
00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:11.400
For the box of the ear that theprince gave you,

275
00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:13.230
he gave it like a rude prince,

276
00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:16.230
and you took it like a sensiblelord.

277
00:13:16.230 --> 00:13:18.770
I have chequed him for it, andthe young lion repents.

278
00:13:18.770 --> 00:13:20.670
Marry, not in ashes andsackcloth,

279
00:13:20.670 --> 00:13:23.900
but in new silk and old sack.

280
00:13:23.900 --> 00:13:25.900
Well, God send the prince abetter companion.

281
00:13:25.900 --> 00:13:28.100
God send the companion a betterprince.

282
00:13:28.100 --> 00:13:29.530
I cannot rid my hands of him.

283
00:13:29.530 --> 00:13:32.370
Well, the king hath severed you.

284
00:13:32.370 --> 00:13:34.800
I hear you are going with LordJohn of Lancaster

285
00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:37.000
against the archbishop and theearl of Northumberland.

286
00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.770
Yea, I thank your pretty sweetwit for it.

287
00:13:40.770 --> 00:13:44.700
But look you pray, all you thatkiss my lady peace at home,

288
00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:46.870
that our armies meet not in ahot day,

289
00:13:46.870 --> 00:13:49.870
for, by the Lord, I take but twoshirts out with me,

290
00:13:49.870 --> 00:13:52.900
and I mean not to sweatextraordinarily.

291
00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:56.030
There is not a dangerous actioncan peep out his head

292
00:13:56.030 --> 00:13:57.330
but I am thrust upon it.

293
00:13:57.330 --> 00:13:59.200
Well, I cannot last ever.

294
00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:02.170
but it was alway yet the trickof our English nation,

295
00:14:02.170 --> 00:14:05.430
if they have a good thing, tomake it too common.

296
00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:07.770
If ye will needs say I'm an oldman,

297
00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:09.730
you should give me rest.

298
00:14:09.730 --> 00:14:11.100
I would to God my name were not

299
00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:13.600
so terrible to the enemy as itis.

300
00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:16.000
I were better to be eaten todeath with a rust

301
00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.300
than to be scoured to nothingwith perpetual motion.

302
00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:24.000
Well, be honest, be honest,

303
00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.870
and God bless your expedition.

304
00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:29.100
Will your lordship lend me£1,000 to furnish me forth?

305
00:14:29.100 --> 00:14:30.700
Not a penny; not a penny.

306
00:14:30.700 --> 00:14:31.830
Fare you well.

307
00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:34.130
Commend me to my cousinWestmoreland.

308
00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:37.930
If I do, fillip me with athree-man beetle.

309
00:14:37.930 --> 00:14:41.230
Boy, what money's in my purse?

310
00:14:45.270 --> 00:14:48.630
Seven groats and two pence.

311
00:14:48.630 --> 00:14:52.230
I can get no remedy against thisconsumption of the purse.

312
00:14:52.230 --> 00:14:54.270
Borrowing only lingers andlingers it out,

313
00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:55.700
but the disease is incurable.

314
00:14:55.700 --> 00:15:01.430
Go bear this letter to my lordof Lancaster,

315
00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:03.070
this to the prince,

316
00:15:03.070 --> 00:15:06.370
this to the earl ofWestmoreland,

317
00:15:06.370 --> 00:15:08.100
and this to old mistress Ursula,

318
00:15:08.100 --> 00:15:10.270
whom I have weekly sworn tomarry

319
00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:12.000
since I perceived the firstwhite hair on my chin.

320
00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.000
About it.

321
00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.100
You know where to find me.

322
00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:22.870
A pox of this gout or a gout ofthis pox,

323
00:15:22.870 --> 00:15:26.400
for the one or the other playsthe rogue with my great toe.

324
00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:29.730
Well, 'tis no matter if I dohalt.

325
00:15:29.730 --> 00:15:31.570
I have the wars for my color,

326
00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:34.170
and my pension shall seem themore reasonable.

327
00:15:34.170 --> 00:15:37.800
A good wit will make use ofanything.

328
00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:41.170
I will turn diseases tocommodity.

329
00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:48.230
Thus have you heard our causeand known our means.

330
00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:50.630
My most noble friends, I prayyou all,

331
00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:54.470
speak plainly your opinions ofour hopes.

332
00:15:58.330 --> 00:16:00.600
Our present musters grow uponthe file

333
00:16:00.600 --> 00:16:02.930
to 25,000 men of choice,

334
00:16:02.930 --> 00:16:04.830
and our supplies live largely

335
00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:06.570
in the hopes of greatNorthumberland,

336
00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:10.370
whose bosom burns with anincensed fire of injuries.

337
00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:16.100
The question then, LordHastings, standeth thus:

338
00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.870
whether our present 25,000

339
00:16:18.870 --> 00:16:21.130
may hold up head withoutNorthumberland?

340
00:16:21.130 --> 00:16:22.630
With him, we may.

341
00:16:22.630 --> 00:16:25.630
Aye, marry, there's the point.

342
00:16:25.630 --> 00:16:28.030
But if without him we be thoughttoo feeble,

343
00:16:28.030 --> 00:16:31.270
my judgment is, we should notstep too far

344
00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:34.730
till we had his assistance bythe hand.

345
00:16:34.730 --> 00:16:37.100
For in a theme so bloody facedas this,

346
00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:41.130
conjecture, expectation, andsurmise of aids incertain

347
00:16:41.130 --> 00:16:42.100
should not be admitted.

348
00:16:42.100 --> 00:16:43.500
Very true, Lord Bardolph,

349
00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:46.800
for indeed it was youngHotspur's case at Shrewsbury.

350
00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:49.270
It was, my lord, who linedhimself with hopes,

351
00:16:49.270 --> 00:16:51.770
eating the air on promise ofsupply,

352
00:16:51.770 --> 00:16:53.730
flattering himself in project ofa power

353
00:16:53.730 --> 00:16:56.570
much smaller than the smallestof his thoughts.

354
00:16:56.570 --> 00:17:00.300
And so with great imaginationproper to madmen,

355
00:17:00.300 --> 00:17:03.800
led his powers to death andwinking leaped into destruction.

356
00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:05.570
But, by your leave, it never yetdid hurt

357
00:17:05.570 --> 00:17:07.600
to lay down likelihoods andforms of hope.

358
00:17:07.600 --> 00:17:08.800
I think we are a body strongenough,

359
00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:11.030
even as we are, to equal withthe king.

360
00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:13.070
What, is the king but 25,000?

361
00:17:13.070 --> 00:17:14.330
To us no more.

362
00:17:14.330 --> 00:17:16.370
Nay, not so much, Lord Bardolph.

363
00:17:16.370 --> 00:17:18.600
For his divisions, as the timesdo brawl,

364
00:17:18.600 --> 00:17:20.370
Are in three heads:

365
00:17:20.370 --> 00:17:22.930
one power against the French andone against Glendower,

366
00:17:22.930 --> 00:17:26.000
perforce the third must take upus.

367
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.630
So is the unfirm king in threedivided,

368
00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.170
and his coffers sound withhollow poverty and emptiness.

369
00:17:33.170 --> 00:17:35.300
That he should draw his severalstrengths together

370
00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:37.730
and come against us in fullpuissance,

371
00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:39.100
need not be dreaded.

372
00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:43.530
Let us on and publish theoccasion of our arms.

373
00:17:47.630 --> 00:17:52.430
The commonwealth is sick oftheir own choice.

374
00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:55.070
Their overgreedy love hathsurfeited.

375
00:17:55.070 --> 00:17:57.400
They that when Richard livedwould have him die

376
00:17:57.400 --> 00:18:00.970
are now become enamored on hisgrave.

377
00:18:00.970 --> 00:18:04.730
Thou that threw'st dust upon hisgoodly head

378
00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:07.630
when through proud London hecame sighing on

379
00:18:07.630 --> 00:18:11.400
after the admired heels ofBolingbroke.

380
00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:14.230
Shall we go draw our numbers andset on?

381
00:18:14.230 --> 00:18:18.070
We are time's subjects, and timebids be gone.

